  "overview": {
    "h2": "BMW 5 Series E34 — Overview",
    "intro": "The third-generation BMW 5 Series (E34) was produced from November 1987 to June 1996, replacing the E28 and later succeeded by the E39. Initially launched as a four-door sedan in January 1988, the E34 also introduced a \"Touring\" estate body style in September 1992 — a first for the 5 Series. The E34 was the first 5 Series to offer all-wheel drive (525iX) and the first to feature a V8 engine (M60). The engine range spanned four-cylinder, six-cylinder and V8 petrols, plus turbo-diesel six-cylinders. The M5 continued with the high-revving S38 straight-six.",
    "keyFacts": "Platform: BMW E34 • Predecessor: BMW 5 Series E28 • Successor: BMW 5 Series E39 • Sibling body styles in this generation: N/A — E34 is the sole body code (sedan and Touring).",
    "marketIntelligenceLine": "The E34 5 Series generates steady UK specialist enquiries, concentrated on the 525i and 535i as these classic BMWs enter collector-car territory."
  },
  "bestWorstEngines": {
    "items": [
      {
        "slot": "Thin-Data Summary",
        "engine": "",
        "quote": "Thin-Data Fallback mode — one paragraph: The E34 5 Series offers a wide range of engines, but the M50B25 (2.5-litre straight-six in the 525i) is widely regarded as the sweet spot — 192 PS, smooth, reliable and well-supported. The M30B34 (535i) is the classic big-six with 211 PS and bulletproof longevity, though thirstier. For V8 enthusiasts, the M60B40 (540i) delivers 286 PS of effortless power, but cooling system maintenance is critical. The S38B36 and S38B38 M5 engines are future classics — 315–340 PS of naturally aspirated straight-six excellence — but expensive to maintain. The M51D25 diesel (525tds) offers 143 PS and excellent economy but is more complex than the petrols. For most buyers, the 525i (M50B25) represents the best balance of reliability, performance and running costs.",
        "whoItsFor": ""
      }
    ]
  },
